{
  "texts": [
    "On the contrary, the efficacy of a supervised model on a specific task may be constrained by the domain of its training data.Although a number of weak supervision-based ad-hoc approaches to IR are available [24,40,41,70,83,84,103],few studies [65,93] have considered a BERT architecture that relies on weak supervision.",
    "Zhang et al.",
    "proposed a reinforcement learning technique, 𝑅𝑒𝐼𝑛𝑓 𝑜𝑆𝑒𝑙𝑒𝑐𝑡 [65], that can guide ranking models to obtain more useful information.It consists of three components, a state network, an action network, and a training reward, as illustrated in Figure 7.The state network contains an a-d (anchor-document) pair that is fed into the action network to determine whether it should be used.",
    "𝑅𝑒𝐼𝑛𝑓 𝑜𝑆𝑒𝑙𝑒𝑐𝑡 uses the 𝑝𝑜𝑙𝑖𝑐𝑦𝑔𝑟𝑎𝑑𝑖𝑒𝑛𝑡 approach to connect the state network to the action network to select useful a-d pairs for weak supervision.",
    "The remaining a-d pairs are fed into BERT to obtain a reward and then are returned to the state and action networks."
  ]
}